article.description: The Clippers haven't won many close games this season, so finally pulling one out prompted a rare postgame locker room visit from Los Angeles owner Donald Sterling.
article.headline: Odom says owner visit after win important
article.linkText: Sterling visits locker room after Clippers top Bucks
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Clippers haven't won many close games this season, so finally pulling one out prompted a rare postgame locker room visit from Los Angeles owner Donald Sterling. Sterling watched the Clippers shoot 50 percent in a 110-104 victory over Milwaukee on Wednesday night that sent the Bucks to their first three-game losing streak in 2 1/2 months. "We've been in games all year and we ain't finished them. This one we got,'' said Lamar Odom, who was the subject of much praise from Sterling during their friendly conversation. "We got to have him around. He's got to know what we're going through, where our minds are at because it's almost summertime. People want to be here,'' Odom said, referring to the possibility the Clippers could lose himself, Elton Brand, Corey Maggette, Andre Miller and Michael Olowokandi to free agency at season's end. "I hope things go well so that this summer we can make some moves and keep this together. It's important for Mr. Sterling to be back here and talk to him a little bit,'' Odom said. Maggette led six Clippers in double figures with 23 points. Brand added 20 points and Miller had 11 assists for the Clippers, who snapped a two-game losing skid. They had lost six of their previous seven and nine of 11. "We needed to be able to win a close game against a quality team,'' Los Angeles coach Alvin Gentry said. "We shot the ball well. We didn't have those real glaring turnovers that hurt us. That was key.'' The Bucks scored the game's first seven points before the Clippers scored seven straight and took the lead for good late in the first quarter. The Bucks got within one with 1 1/2 minutes remaining, but they managed just one basket the rest of the way. "We let Brand and Maggette get involved,'' Bucks coach George Karl said. "We made it a shootout and it's tough to win one of those on the road.'' Sam Cassell scored 21 points, Ray Allen added 18 points and Michael Redd had 18 points and 11 rebounds for the Bucks, who hadn't dropped three in a row since Dec. 3-7. Allen went scoreless in the fourth, including a miss with 35 seconds left and the Bucks down by four points. "We feel good about what we've been doing, but it's just the little things that eat away at our success,'' Allen said. "I thought I got a lot of my teammates good shots and they converted. If I can get someone a good shot, that's what matters.'' The Bucks got within two on a basket by Tim Thomas with 5:46 remaining. The Clippers held them off by scoring six in a row for a 99-91 lead. Then Thomas and Redd hit consecutive 3-pointers, Cassell scored and the Bucks trailed 101-99 with 2:13 to play. Redd hit a running jumper and made the free throw after getting fouled by Eric Piatkowski to put the Bucks down by one. Anthony Mason turned the ball over at midcourt and Lamar Odom scored on a driving hook, got fouled and made one of two free throws as the Clippers led 106-102 with 47 seconds left. "It was a good game, a positive game for us,'' Brand said. "We need a team effort just like that.'' The Clippers led 60-53 at halftime after shooting 55 percent. Odom hit a 3-pointer for the Clippers' largest lead of the third quarter, 69-59. The Bucks outscored the Clippers 11-6, including a 3-pointer by Cassell and consecutive baskets by Mason, over the final three minutes to trail 80-77 going into the fourth quarter. Brand said it was unlikely Sterling would have paid a visit if the Clippers lost. "He's been to a lot of games and we haven't won a lot. He's happy with this one, definitely,'' he said. "We just say hello and thanks and keep it moving. It's not the time or the place after the game (to discuss the team's future).''

Game notes
Clippers G Keyon Dooling missed the game because of a sprained left arch, while G Quentin Richardson sat out with a cold. ... Cassell needs three points for 10,000 in his 10-year NBA career, which includes four full seasons with Milwaukee. ... Karl needs one win to tie Del Harris for third on Milwaukee's career victories list. Harris had a 191-154 record from 1987-91. Karl is 190-159 in his fifth season. ... Kato Kaelin, a Milwaukee-area native famous for being O.J. Simpson's houseguest in 1994, was booed when he was shown on the big screen before the fourth quarter.
